The sun rises and the sun sets;
panting, it hurries back to the place
where it rises.

9:
What has been is what will be,
and what has been done is what will be done;
there is nothing new under the sun.

17:
I applied my mind to know wisdom and knowledge,
 madness and folly;
 I learned that this too is a pursuit of the wind.

23:
For all his days are filled with grief, and his occupation is sorrowful;
 even at night, his mind does not rest.
 This too is futile.

26:
For to the person who is pleasing in his sight, he gives wisdom, knowledge, and joy;
 but to the sinner he gives the task of gathering and accumulating in order to give to the one who is pleasing in God’s sight.
 This too is futile and a pursuit of the wind.

3:
A man may father a hundred children and live many years. No matter how long he lives,
 if he is not satisfied by good things and does not even have a proper burial,
 I say that a stillborn child is better off than he.

6:
